{"query": "What are the documented benefits and negative impacts of retaining habitat features like riparian buffers, coarse woody debris, and snags during timber harvesting?", "summary": "Studies have documented mixed effects of retaining habitat features during timber harvesting. Riparian buffer strips showed mixed effects on amphibian abundance depending on species and buffer width, with six of 11 studies finding mixed effects depending on species or existing downed wood volume, four finding similar abundance and species composition to unharvested forest, and two finding lower numbers than in unharvested forest. Two of four studies found greater amphibian species numbers and abundance in wider riparian buffers (Action ID: 747).

For coarse woody debris, two replicated controlled studies found no significant difference in abundance for eight of nine amphibian species between clearcuts with debris retained versus removed, though overall amphibian response was more negative where debris was retained. One study found juvenile amphibian survival was significantly higher in woody debris piles than open areas within clearcuts. For mammals, three studies showed mixed results, with one finding more small mammal species groups in felled areas with woody debris, while two found no increase in small mammal numbers with retained debris (Action ID: 843, 2647).

Regarding snags/standing deadwood, two studies found mixed effects on reptile diversity and abundance when adding snags and woody debris compared to no manipulation or debris removal. One study found no effect of increasing standing coarse woody debris on reptile diversity or abundance (Action ID: 3631, 845).", "action_ids": ["747", "3631", "843", "845", "2647"]}

